199. Et trepidum solvunt, &c. “ And the blast of the horn mingled with the clarion’s peal act as a cathartie from terror.” More literally “ cause your bowels to become loose through terror.”—Lituis. The word lituus was employed by the Latin writers to denote (1) the crooked staff borne by the augurs, with which they divided the expanse of heaven, when viewed with reference to divination (templum), into regions (re- yiones). (2) a sort of trumpet slightly curved at the extremity. It differ- ed both from the tuba and the cornu, the former being straight, while the latter was bent round into a spiral shape. Lydus calls the lituus the sacerdotal trumpet (ἱερατικὴν σάλπιγγα), and says that it was employed by Romulus when he proclaimed the title of his city. Acro asserts that it was peculiar to cavalry, while the tuba belonged to infantry. Its tones are usually characterised as harsh and shrill. Miiller supposes the word lituus to be Etruscan, signifying “ crooked.'' The cornu was called in Greek στρογγύλη wamy& and was curved nearly in the shape of a C.
